Understanding UPI Fraud

UPI fraud is a common type of online scam that happens through digital payment apps like PhonePe, Google Pay, Paytm, and BHIM.
In most cases, there is no actual hacking involved. Instead, the fraud depends on misleading the user into taking an action 
themselves, such as entering their UPI PIN when they shouldn’t. Because the user unknowingly authorizes the transaction, the 
fraud becomes very effective and hard to reverse.

How the Scam Works (Step-by-Step)

Example: Fake Payment Request Scam

Rohit, a second-year student, lists his old laptop for sale on OLX. Soon, he gets a message from someone claiming to be 
interested in buying it and offering to pay via Google Pay.
The scammer sends a “request” on Google Pay. This request can easily be mistaken for receiving money, especially if the user
is not familiar with how UPI works.
The scammer then calls or messages Rohit, pretending to be from Google Pay support. He says there is a small verification step
and asks Rohit to enter his UPI PIN.
Assuming he is about to receive the payment, Rohit enters his PIN without realizing the risk.
In reality, this action authorizes a payment. Within seconds, ₹18,000 is transferred from Rohit’s account to the scammer.
After the transaction, the scammer blocks Rohit, making it impossible to contact him.
Who is More Likely to Be Targeted?
Students or individuals selling items online (OLX, Quikr, Facebook Marketplace)
People who are new to UPI and unaware of how payment requests work
Individuals who respond quickly under pressure, as scammers often create urgency
Impact and Consequences

The money lost in such scams is usually gone instantly, and recovering it is very difficult. Although banks may help if
informed quickly, many people realize the fraud too late. Apart from financial loss, victims also face stress and regret, 
as the scam is designed to look completely genuine.
